05614nam a22008295i 9783110633030DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021939452  a97831106330307 a10.1515/97831106330302doi  a(DE-B1597)503562  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh00aGreek and Latin Love :bThe Poetic Connection /ced. by Thea S. Thorsen, Stephen Harrison, Iris Brecke. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 267 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroducing Greek and Latin Love: The Poetic Connection -- tLove: Ancient and Later Representations -- tThere Falls a Lone Tear: Longing for a Vanished Love – Tracing an Erotic Motif from Homer to Horace -- tOrpheus and Sappho as Model Poets: Blurring Greek and Latin Love in Lament for Bion, Catullus 51, and Horace Odes 1.24 -- tAmans et Egens and Exclusus Amator: The Connection (or not) between Comedy and Elegy -- tRape and Violence in Terence’s Eunuchus and Ovid’s Love Elegies -- tLove and Poetry in Virgil’s Sixth Eclogue: A Platonic Perspective -- tLongum Bibebat Amorem: Virgilian Adaptation of Sympotic Poetry -- tPhilodemus and the Augustan Poets -- tLove and Politics in Horace’s Odes 4.10 -- tAmores Plural: Ovidian Homoerotics in the Elegies -- tThe Beloved: Figures and Words -- tList of Contributors -- tBibliography -- tIndex Locorum -- tIndex Rerum0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIt is often claimed that the kind of love that is variously deemed 'romantic' or 'true' did not exist in antiquity. Yet, ancient literature abounds with stories that seem to adhere precisely to this kind of love. This volume focuses on such literature and the concepts of love it espouses. The volume differs from and challenges much existing classical scholarship which has traditionally privileged the theme of sex over love and prose-genres over those of poetry. By conversely focusing on love and poetry, the present volume freshly explores central poets in ancient literature, such Homer, Sappho, Terence, Catullus, Virgil, Horace and Ovid, alongside less canonized, such as the anonymous poet of The Lament for Bion, Philodemus and Sulpicia. The chapters, which are written by world-leading as well as younger scholars, reveal that Greek and Latin concepts of love seem interconnected, that such love is as relevant for hetero- as homoerotic couples, and that such ideas of love follow the mainstream of poetry throughout antiquity. In addition to the general reader interested in the history of love, this volume is relevant for students and scholars of the ancient world and the poetic tradition.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 4aElegie. 4aLiebe ‹Motiv›. 4aLiebesgeschichte. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aGreek and Latin.  aLove.  ahetero- and homoerotic.  apoetry.1 aAcosta-Hughes, Benjamin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAstrup Sundt, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrecke, Iris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrecke, Iris, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aD’Andrea, Paola, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Stephen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aIngleheart, Jennifer, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKayachev, Boris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKeith, Alison, eco